 access with authorization2star  aThe Islamic world, often regarded as an anathema to civil society, in fact has rich traditions of associational life pursuing “common good”. These religious resources have been reinterpreted for the enhancement of civic virtues and participatory politics in contemporary context, that is, democratization. Such pioneering efforts have been clearly observable in Muslim Southeast Asia. In November 1999, the Sasakawa Peace Foundation invited ten Muslim activists and scholars from the region to Japan for exchanging views and experiences among themselves and with Japanese participants. Here their papers and discussions are compiled into a book, Islam and Civil Society in Southeast Asia.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aCivil society--Religious aspects--Islam. 0aCivil society--Southeast Asia. 0aIslamy20th century--Southeast Asia. 0aIslam--Social aspects--Southeast Asia. 0aIslam--Southeast Asia. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology of Religion.2bisacsh1 aAbdullah, M. Amin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBajunid, Omar Farouk, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBajunid, Omar Farouk, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBakar, Mohamad Abu, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBakar, Osman, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFalaakh, Mohammad Fajrul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHassan, Sharifah Zaleha Syed, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMadjid, Nurcholish, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMastura, Michael O., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMitsuo, Nakamura, econtributor.4ctb4https://id